rent market is depicted with numerous stalls occupying temporary stalls of light materials that cannot withstand all-weather conditions and far from the sanitary and hygienic place where, especially, food items are sold for households in the area to consume. The stalls are also not uniform in space, and many vendors occupy the roadside, adding to the chaos brought by the lack of a proper parking area for vehicles and sidewalk for people.\",\"description_services\":\"Making available the commercial spaces for utilization and collection of fees in form of fixed monthly rentals from users of market facility and other amenities such as parking and rental spaces. Provision of support facilities such as drinking water, toilets and showers, solid waste management, 24\\/7 security, power backup.\",\"reasons_ppp\":\"With the DBFOM (User pay) model the concessionaire assumes the revenue risk, provided with freedom, flexibility and motivation to develop, operate and generate rate of return to recover the project lifecycle costs. Such arrangement entails the responsibility of revenue collection as well as demand generation is vested with the Private Partner. During operations, the private partner will share revenue with the Implementing Authority in form of a variable payment (Annual Concession Fee), which will be the bid parameter.  With this model, the Implementing Authority shall create an enabling environment for successful development of the project that shall be attractive for investors.\",\"stakeholder_consultation\":\"During the surveys conducted at Feasibility Study stage, a total of 188 market traders in Mwanakwerekwe, of which 104 or 55% were from the main markets, and the rest from the Annex. The survey was important to understand the current situation from the target beneficiaries\\u2019 viewpoint. The observations from the community engagements, and the results from the survey were consistent with regards to people\\u2019s anticipation of the proposed project. Some of the project benefits identified by the target beneficiaries included: (1) better\\/cleaner environment may impact on health and eliminate hazards (2) comfort and safety for all traders and buyers, (3) better security in the area, (4) potential to attract tourists to purchase items from the market, (5) having a feeling of pride and dignity in trading, and (6) more flexible trading hours. These perceived benefits influence the high acceptability of the project from the viewpoint of the target beneficiaries, indicating that the proposed project will bring about positive impact on the overall well-being of the public.\",\"description_asset\":\"The various facilities proposed within the market complex include commercial stalls, and ATM, Auction platform, Office Space for market administration office and rental, parking for cars and two wheelers as well as other amenities such as community hall, prayer room, open space and pedestrian walkways.\",\"project_summary_document\":\"\",\"project_value_usd\":7.83,\"project_value_second\":18800,\"ppp_delivery_model_id\":2},\"old\":{\"project_id\":32,\"sponsor_id\":1,\"ocid\":\"ocds-aaaaaa-32\",\"stage_id\":1,\"project_need\":\"Mwanakwerekwe market is one of the two busiest markets in the Urban West area, currently serving about 2000 traders (including stall and shop assistants) operating in Mwanakwerekwe, with about 500 spilling out of the formal market area and setting up temporary stalls just outside. The current market is depicted with numerous stalls occupying temporary stalls of light materials that cannot withstand all-weather conditions and far from the sanitary and hygienic place where, especially, food items are sold for households in the area to consume. The stalls are also not uniform in space, and many vendors occupy the roadside, adding to the chaos brought by the lack of a proper parking area for vehicles and sidewalk for people.\",\"description_services\":\"Making available the commercial spaces for utilization and collection of fees in form of fixed monthly rentals from users of market facility and other amenities such as parking and rental spaces. Provision of support facilities such as drinking water, toilets and showers, solid waste management, 24\\/7 security, power backup.\",\"reasons_ppp\":\"With the DBFOM (User pay) model the concessionaire assumes the revenue risk, provided with freedom, flexibility and motivation to develop, operate and generate rate of return to recover the project lifecycle costs. Such arrangement entails the responsibility of revenue collection as well as demand generation is vested with the Private Partner. During operations, the private partner will share revenue with the Implementing Authority in form of a variable payment (Annual Concession Fee), which will be the bid parameter.  With this model, the Implementing Authority shall create an enabling environment for successful development of the project that shall be attractive for investors.\",\"stakeholder_consultation\":\"During the surveys conducted at Feasibility Study stage, a total of 188 market traders in Mwanakwerekwe, of which 104 or 55% were from the main markets, and the rest from the Annex. The survey was important to understand the current situation from the target beneficiaries\\u2019 viewpoint. The observations from the community engagements, and the results from the survey were consistent with regards to people\\u2019s anticipation of the proposed project. Some of the project benefits identified by the target beneficiaries included: (1) better\\/cleaner environment may impact on health and eliminate hazards (2) comfort and safety for all traders and buyers, (3) better security in the area, (4) potential to attract tourists to purchase items from the market, (5) having a feeling of pride and dignity in trading, and (6) more flexible trading hours. These perceived benefits influence the high acceptability of the project from the viewpoint of the target beneficiaries, indicatin