ne_category_id\":null}}','2020-06-17 22:40:03','2020-06-17 22:40:03'),(293,'default','updated',127,'App\\Models\\Project\\ContractMilestones\\ContractMilestone',1,'App\\User','{\"attributes\":{\"project_id\":32,\"name\":\"Project proposal received\",\"milestone_type_id\":2,\"date\":\"2016-06-21 00:00:00\",\"description\":\"Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet, consectetur adipiscing elit.\",\"milestone_category_id\":null},\"old\":{\"project_id\":32,\"name\":\"Project proposal received12\",\"milestone_type_id\":2,\"date\":\"2016-06-21 00:00:00\",\"description\":\"Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet, consectetur adipiscing elit.\",\"milestone_category_id\":null}}','2020-06-17 22:40:10','2020-06-17 22:40:10'),(294,'default','updated',47,'App\\Models\\Project\\ProjectInformation',13,'App\\User','{\"attributes\":{\"project_id\":47,\"sponsor_id\":3,\"ocid\":\"ocds-aaaaaa-47\",\"stage_id\":2,\"project_need\":\"Zanzibar imports its bulk petroleum products (kerosene, aviation fuel, petrol and diesel) through the Mtoni terminal on Unguja Island. The terminal is located in a World Heritage buffer zone and adjoins tourism and residential areas. The Mtoni terminal no longer meets the needs of Zanzibar: It is too small to meet growing demand. Because of encroaching urban development, expansion is not possible; Shallow draughts, aggravated by silting, constrain the size of vessels that can berth. Increasingly frequent shipments are required from small vessels, adding to transport costs and fuel prices in Zanzibar; Inefficient operations also add to transport costs and fuel prices; The potential for oil spills is too high; and Small storage capacity means that security of supply is not assured. This project therefore contemplates construction and operation of a high standard petroleum terminal, on Unguja Island, in the Bumbwini\\/Mangapwani region of approximately 380 hectares, 22 kilometres north of the existing Mtoni terminal. This will allow larger shipments and more efficient handling, thereby minimizing shipment costs. The unloading times of shippers and loading time of buyers will be reduced. Increase storage capacity and better access by vessels will improve security of supply. The project will be implemented in an environmentally sustainable manner. The risk to human life and the environment will also be reduced by re-locating the facility away from environmentally and culturally sensitive urban areas.\",\"description_services\":\"The private partner shall install sufficient storage capacity and the necessary systems to ensure that stock outs do not occur at the importation facility to reduce the cost of fuel in Zanzibar and improve energy security. The private operator will also collect revenues on a commercial basis from customers using the facility. The terminal fees of the private operator will be approved by ZURA to ensure that the monopoly position of the operator is does not lead to higher prices for consumers.\",\"reasons_ppp\":\"The proposed form of contracts are Build operate transfer (BOT) or Design, Build, Finance, Operate and Maintain (DBFOM) whereby, private partner will be responsible for financing, installation, operation and maintenance of the ZLT facility for the period specified in the agreement. The public partner will provide the exclusive right to the private partner to import petroleum products for the local market. All fuel products will be covered with the exclusion of LPG. Competition will be allowed in the LPG sector as there is already an operator in Mangapwani with advanced plans to develop a liquefied petroleum gas (LPG) importation facility under a ZIPA permit.\",\"stakeholder_consultation\":\"The primary stakeholders are the oil marketing companies (OMCs), ZURA, Zanzibar Port Corporation (ZPC), Ministry of Infrastructure, Zanzibar Maritime Authority (ZMA) and consumers. There appears to be good support for the project from the primary stakeholders. There are, however, some potentially competing private sector operations in planning that may express concerns in been displaced by ZLT.\",\"description_asset\":\"Jetty, inclusive of dolphins, loading platform and trestle, piles and foundations, and piping; the tank farm; utility and building works; and transport infrastructure.\",\"project_summary_document\":\"\",\"project_value_usd\":40,\"project_value_second\":96000,\"ppp_delivery_model_id\":2},\"old\":{\"project_id\":47,\"sponsor_id\":7,\"ocid\":\"ocds-aaaaaa-47\",\"stage_id\":3,\"project_need\":\"Zanzibar imports its bulk petroleum products (kerosene, aviation fuel, petrol and diesel) through the Mtoni terminal on Unguja Island. The terminal is located in a World Heritage buffer zone and adjoins tourism and residential areas. The Mtoni terminal no longer meets the needs of Zanzibar: It is too small to meet growing demand. Because of encroaching urban development, expansion is not possible; Shallow draughts, aggravated by silting, constrain the size of vessels that can berth. Increasingly frequent shipments are required from small vessels, adding to transport costs and fuel prices in Zanzibar; Inefficient operations also add to transport costs and fuel prices; The potential for oil spills is too high; and Small storage capacity means that security of supply is not assured. This project therefore contemplates construction and operation of a high standard petroleum terminal, on Unguja Island, in the Bumbwini\\/Mangapwani region of approximately 380 hectares, 22 kilometres north of the existing Mtoni terminal. This will allow larger shipments and more efficient handling, thereby minimizing shipment costs. The unloading times of shippers and loading time of buyers will be reduced. Increase storage capacity and better access by vessels will improve security of supply. The project will be implemented in an environmentally sustainable manner. The risk to human life and the environment will also be reduced by re-locating the facility away from environmentally and culturally sensitive urban areas.\",\"description_services\":\"The private partner shall install sufficient storage capacity and the necessary systems to ensure that stock outs do not occur at the importation facility to reduce the cost of fuel in Zanzibar and improve energy security. The private operator will also collect revenues on a commercial basis from customers using the facility. The terminal fees of the private operator will be approved by ZURA to ensure that the monopoly position of the operator is does not lead to higher prices for consumers.\",\"reasons_ppp\":\"The proposed form of contracts are Build operate transfer (BOT) or Design, Build, Finance, Operate and Maintain (DBFOM) whereby, private partner will be responsible for financing, installation, operation and maintenance of the ZLT facility for the period specified in the agreement. The public partner will provide the exclusive right to the private partner to import petroleum products for the local market. All fuel products will be covered with the exclusion of LPG. Competition will be allowed in the LPG sector as there is already an operator in Mangapwani with advanced plans to develop a liquefied petroleum gas (LPG) importation facility under a ZIPA permit.\",\"stakeholder_consultation\":\"The primary stakeholders are the oil marketing companies (OMCs), ZURA, Zanzibar Port Corporation (ZPC), Ministry of Infrastructure, Zanzibar Maritime Authority (ZMA) and consumers. There appears to be good support for the project from the primary stakeholders. There are, however, some potentially competing private sector operations in planning that may express concerns in been displaced by ZLT.\",\"description_asset\":\"Jetty, inclusive of dolphins, loading platform and trestle, piles and foundations, and piping; the tank farm; utility and building works; and transport infrastructure.\",\"project_summary_document\":\"\",\"project_value_usd\":40,\"project_value_second\":96000,\"ppp_delivery_model_id\":null}}','2020-06-25 06:36:24','2020-06-