INSERT INTO `project_information` VALUES (32,32,1,'ocds-aaaaaa-32',1,'Mwanakwerekwe market is one of the two busiest markets in the Urban West area, currently serving about 2000 traders (including stall and shop assistants) operating in Mwanakwerekwe, with about 500 spilling out of the formal market area and setting up temporary stalls just outside. The current market is depicted with numerous stalls occupying temporary stalls of light materials that cannot withstand all-weather conditions and far from the sanitary and hygienic place where, especially, food items are sold for households in the area to consume. The stalls are also not uniform in space, and many vendors occupy the roadside, adding to the chaos brought by the lack of a proper parking area for vehicles and sidewalk for people.',1,'Making available the commercial spaces for utilization and collection of fees in form of fixed monthly rentals from users of market facility and other amenities such as parking and rental spaces. Provision of support facilities such as drinking water, toilets and showers, solid waste management, 24/7 security, power backup.',1,'With the DBFOM (User pay) model the concessionaire assumes the revenue risk, provided with freedom, flexibility and motivation to develop, operate and generate rate of return to recover the project lifecycle costs. Such arrangement entails the responsibility of revenue collection as well as demand generation is vested with the Private Partner. During operations, the private partner will share revenue with the Implementing Authority in form of a variable payment (Annual Concession Fee), which will be the bid parameter.  With this model, the Implementing Authority shall create an enabling environment for successful development of the project that shall be attractive for investors.',1,'During the surveys conducted at Feasibility Study stage, a total of 188 market traders in Mwanakwerekwe, of which 104 or 55% were from the main markets, and the rest from the Annex. The survey was important to understand the current situation from the target beneficiaries viewpoint. The observations from the community engagements, and the results from the survey were consistent with regards to peoples anticipation of the proposed project. Some of the project benefits identified by the target beneficiaries included: (1) better/cleaner environment may impact on health and eliminate hazards (2) comfort and safety for all traders and buyers, (3) better security in the area, (4) potential to attract tourists to purchase items from the market, (5) having a feeling of pride and dignity in trading, and (6) more flexible trading hours. These perceived benefits influence the high acceptability of the project from the viewpoint of the target beneficiaries, indicating that the proposed project will bring about positive impact on the overall well-being of the public.',1,'The various facilities proposed within the market complex include commercial stalls, and ATM, Auction platform, Office Space for market administration office and rental, parking for cars and two wheelers as well as other amenities such as community hall, prayer room, open space and pedestrian walkways.',1,'',1,783000.00000,18800.00000,0,0,0,NULL,1,NULL,'2020-06-17 21:07:02',NULL,NULL,NULL,1,2),(33,33,1,'ocds-aaaaaa-33',1,'Mombasa Market is known in the Urban West Region as the primary receiver of wholesale products imported from Pemba Island. From here, wholesale orders can be made, for retailing to other markets such as Darajani and Mwanakwerekwe. Many households in the area also purchase goods from Mombasa Market for their daily needs. Based on an inventory by the Urban Municipal Council (UMC), there are currently about 696 traders operating in the market, there are also about 23 temporary stalls built outside its periphery. The current Mombasa Market is depicted with numerous stalls occupying temporary stalls of light materials that cannot withstand all-weather conditions. Because of this, the UMC proposed for the redevelopment of the Mombasa public market. The redeveloped market and improved services will provide market stalls for wet and dry goods, commercial space for lease, essential amenities, parking space, pathways and open spaces for ease mobility within the public market',1,'Making available the commercial spaces for utilization and collection of fees in form of fixed monthly rentals from users of market facility and other amenities such as parking and rental spaces. Provision of support facilities such as drinking water, toilets and showers, solid waste management, 24/7 security, power backup.',1,'With the DBFOM (User pay) model the concessionaire assumes the revenue risk, provided with freedom, flexibility and motivation to develop, operate and generate rate of return to recover the project lifecycle costs. With this model, the Implementing Authority shall create an enabling environment for successful development of the project that shall be attractive for investors.',1,'During the surveys conducted at Feasibility Study stage, 121 market traders were interviewed, representing 17.4% of the total number of traders selling goods and offering services there, as inventoried by the UMC. The survey was important to understand the current situation from the target beneficiaries viewpoint. 93% of all those interviewed were excited with the prospect of having the market redeveloped, as promoted by the local government. The UMC has held community engagements to gather traders opinions and support for the plan. The observations from the\ncommunity engagements, and the results from the survey were consistent with regards to peoples anticipation of the proposed project. Some of the project benefits identified by the target beneficiaries included: (1) better/cleaner environment may impact on health and eliminate hazards (2) comfort and safety for all traders and buyers, (3) better security in the area, (4) potential to attract tourists to purchase items from the market, (5) having a feeling of pride and dignity in trading, and (6) more flexible trading hours. These perceived benefits influence the high acceptability of the project from the viewpoint of the target beneficiaries, indicating that the proposed project will bring about positive impact on the overall well-being of the public.',1,'The various facilities proposed within the market complex include commercial stalls, shops and ATM, Office Space for market administration office and rental, parking for cars and two wheelers as well as other amenities such as community hall, prayer room, open space and pedestrian walkways.',1,'',1,4.00000,9715.00000,0,0,0,NULL,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,1,NULL),(34,34,1,'ocds-aaaaaa-34',1,'The proposed site in Kijangwani currently serves as a temporary transport terminal serving the Urban West Region, where most of Zanzibars commercial and government establishments are located, is a convergence point in Unguja island. Many people from the different districts, commute daily via buses and daladala for various purposes such as work, schooling, and trading. The site is located in the close proximity in close proximity to the Darajani Market and the touristy Stone Town, two busiest centres of urban west region. Most of the passengers are picked up along the Kaunda Road in front of the Mnazi Mmoja Hospital. As the capital of country, Urban West Region is anticipating more people and economic activities in the future putting pressure on the current temporary terminal. The current temporary bus terminal does not have proper facilities to run smoothly, like alighting and boarding bays, passenger waiting area/ passenger concourse, ticketing, idle parking, separate entry and exit, help desk, information display, toilets, food stall, etc. The proposed bus terminal will be fully equipped with these facilities adequately to cater the need of commuters, daladala operators and the citizens in general.',1,'Making available the passenger concourse, departure bus bays, Alighting bus bays, Idle bus bays, Overnight bus parking, Ticketing counters, Bus schedule display and monitoring, Public address system, Workshop for repairs, Public amenities, Driver rest room, Bus operators booths/offices, Commercial spaces, Prayer rooms, Parking for private vehicles for utilization. Collection of fees in form of terminal fee, to be paid by the buses/daladalas, and feed from other amenities such as parking and rental spaces. Provision of support facilities such as drinking water, toilets and showers, solid waste management, 24/7 security, power backup.',1,'With the DBFOM (User pay) model the concessionaire assumes the revenue risk, provided with freedom, flexibility and motivation to develop, operate and generate rate of return to recover the project lifecycle costs. Such arrangement entails the responsibility of revenue collection as well as demand generation is vested with the Private Partner. During operations, the private partner will share revenue with the Implementing Authority in form of a variable payment (Annual Concession Fee), which will be the bid parameter With this model, the Implementing Authority shall create an enabling environment for successful development of the project that shall be attractive for investors.',1,'Survey launched during the Feasibility Study enabled the council to understand the current situation from the target beneficiaries viewpoint. Interview was conducted with 43 drivers and 42 passengers where 74% of the drivers and 88% of the passengers stated that if a terminal facility will be established within the vicinity, they will be supportive of it. Some of the project benefits identified included: (1) comfort and safety, (2) better security in the area, (3) better/cleaner environment may impact on health and eliminate hazards, and (4) potential to attract tourists to use public transport. These perceived benefits influence the high acceptability of the project from the viewpoint of the target beneficiaries, indicating that the proposed project will bring about positive impact on the overall well-being of the public.',1,'The various facilities proposed within the bus terminal complex include circulation with Passenger concourse, Departure bus bays, Alighting bus bays, Idle bus bays, Passenger waiting area,  Commercial space including Fast food corners, Shops, Kiosks, Bank ATMs, Office Space, Bus Terminal, Administration Office, Transporters Office, Rental Office, Parking for cars and two wheelers and others amenities such as drivers rest room, prayer rooms, public conveniences as well as open space.',1,'',1,7.45000,17871.00000,0,0,0,NULL,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,1,NULL),(36,36,5,'ocds-aaaaaa-36',1,'Pemba Island has four districts and Chakechake is among the two in the Kusini or Southern Region. The location of the Pemba airport makes Chakechake the gateway for tourism and one of the convergence points in the island. Many people from the different districts, commute daily via buses and daladala for various purposes such as work, and trading. However, the town of Chakechake currently has a temporary terminal facility in an open space in the midst of the busy area of Central Business District (CBD) of town, surrounded by market and some residential buildings. There are no proper waiting areas for commuters especially during rush hours. The temporary terminal is depicted as chaotic, and congested. The council has established a toll gate for cars passing from the northern region, and another for those passing from the southern region. Toll gate keepers collect a one-time daily Tsh 1,000 per PUV for the use of the temporary terminals. This prompted the council to propose a proper terminal facility.',1,'Making available the passenger concourse, departure bus bays, Alighting bus bays, Idle bus bays, Overnight bus parking, Ticketing counters, Bus schedule display and monitoring, Public address system, Workshop for repairs, Public amenities, Driver rest room, Bus operators booths/offices, Commercial spaces, Prayer rooms, Parking for private vehicles for utilization. Collection of fees in form of terminal fee, to be paid by the buses/daladalas, and feed from other amenities such as parking and rental spaces. Provision of support facilities such as drinking water, toilets and showers, solid waste management, 24/7 security, power backup.',1,'With the DBFOM (User pay) model the concessionaire assumes the revenue risk, provided with freedom, flexibility and motivation to develop, operate and generate rate of return to recover the project lifecycle costs. Such arrangement entails the responsibility of revenue collection as well as demand generation is vested with the Private Partner. During operations, the private partner will share revenue with the Implementing Authority in form of a variable payment (Annual Concession Fee), which will be the bid parameter With this model, the Implementing Authority shall create an enabling environment for successful development of the project that shall be attractive for investors',1,'Launched during the Feasibility Study enabled the council to understand the current situation from the target beneficiaries viewpoint. Interview was conducted with 65 drivers representing about 19% of the 349 registered PUVs in 2019. Of these, 71% expressed support to CTCs proposal for a better terminal that will address the issues. While among the 65 passengers interviewed, 72% expressed support. Some of the project benefits identified included: (1) more convenience parking and terminal space, (2) comfort and safety for passengers and drivers, (3) potential to attract tourists to use public conveyance, (4) better/cleaner environment may impact on health, (5) more order within the streets of Chakechake, and (6) avoidance of accidents caused by the narrow and singular entry/exit point and the lack of space for safe manoeuvring. These perceived benefits influence the high acceptability from the viewpoint of the target beneficiaries, indicating that the project will bring about positive impact on the overall well-being of the public.',1,'The various facilities proposed within the bus terminal complex include circulation with Passenger concourse, Departure bus bays, Alighting bus bays, Idle bus bays, Passenger waiting area,  Commercial space including Fast food corners, Shops, Kiosks, Bank ATMs, Office Space, Bus Terminal, Administration Office, Transporters Office, Rental Office, Parking for cars and two wheelers and others amenities such as drivers rest room, prayer rooms, public conveniences as well as open space.',1,'',1,3.37000,8088.00000,0,0,0,NULL,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,1,NULL),(37,37,4,'ocds-aaaaaa-37',1,'Established in the Fumba Economic Zone, the International Trade and Conventional Centre is a flagship project strategically created to optimize the tourism opportunity of the isles for regional and international events. The project objective is realized through a modern international trade and convention centre (ITCC) that will be at par with world standards and attractive to the dynamic meetings, incentives, conferences and exhibitions (MICE) industry. The proposed ITCC will provide facilities like convention centre, exhibition halls, hotel accommodation, offices, residential apartments and other amenities. Currently there is no ITCC in Zanzibar. ITCC will therefore help in promoting tourism and attract more holiday makers and business travellers. Key benefits of the project include enhanced tourism, improved trade, job creation, enhancement in Tax revenue, improvement in infrastructure as well as increase in land values in the adjacent areas.',1,'Detailed design, construction methodology, quality assurance procedures, and the procurement, engineering and construction for completion of the project. At its own cost and expense, procure finance for and undertake the design, engineering, procurement, construction, operation and maintenance of the project assets and observe, fulfil, comply with and perform all its obligations set out in the PPP Agreement. Obtain Applicable Permits to perform its obligations during the project team and keep in force and effect such applicable permits in conformity with applicable laws. Permit safe, smooth and uninterrupted flow of operations, project assets during normal operating conditions. Collect the user fees and its appropriation by the private partner. Operation and maintenance of all communication, control and administrative system necessary for efficient operation of the project assets by the private partner. Maintain public relations unit or a grievance redressal cell to interface with and attend to suggestions from users, government agencies, media and other agencies by the private partner.',1,'DBFOM (user pay) and DBFOM (ABP) offer value for money and present good returns for the project. However, DBFOM (User Pay) model offers better VFM than DBFOM (ABP). From a private investor perspective, ABP would be more attractive as the risk is limited and there are guaranteed payments from the government. However, it is important to note that the project is one of the flagship projects intended to put Zanzibar in world map as one of leading MICE destinations. This would require a great effort in terms of the marketing the project facilities through a well-crafted & executed marketing strategy which is not the Authoritys forte and again the Authority would be dependent on the third-party marketing agents. The project business is dynamic in nature and subject to frequent changes which warrant instant responses to market dynamics wherein there could be certain limitations for the Authority. In absence of a robust mechanism to optimize the revenues, it would be extremely difficult to create a sustainable template for the project vision to develop Zanzibar into a world class MICE destination. In light of the above facts and foregoing discussions, it is recommended that the project may be implemented through the DBFOM (user pay) model wherein the Concessionaire assumes the revenue risk, is provided with the freedom, flexibility and motivation to develop, operate and generate rate of return to recover the project lifecycle costs. The Authority shall create an enabling environment for successful development of the project that shall be attractive for the investors.',1,'',1,'The various facilities proposed within the ITCC include one Convention Centre with two floors, Five exhibition halls of single floors, a hotel block with three floors, office building  with three floors, one stop centre with two floors, a medical centre with a single floor, club and amenities with two floors and two apartment buildings with five floors each.',1,'',1,44.03000,105662.00000,0,0,0,NULL,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,1,NULL),(38,38,1,'ocds-aaaaaa-38',1,'The Urban West Region, where most of Zanzibars commercial and government establishments are located, is a convergence point in Unguja island. Many people from the different districts, commute daily using private vehicle. The trends of increasing new car registrations and new licenses is not seen to decline in the next years. Hundreds of cars are parked by the roadside, there are designated parking spaces in the urban core, but these are depicted to be very muddy during the rainy season, and dusty during the summer. As the capital of country, Urban West Region is anticipating more people and economic activities in the future putting pressure on current infrastructure and services. One of the key problems in the region is that there is a lack of a parking facility that could be used for the orderly parking of private vehicles used by the local population, the tourists, and other Zanzibaris travelling to or from the northern and southern regions of Unguja. The current temporary parking sites at Darajani do not have proper facilities, like standardized parking bays, exit, entry, ticketing, toilets, etc. The proposed car parking will be fully equipped with these facilities adequately to cater the need of parkers.',1,'Making available the parking bays, collection of fees in form of parking fee, to be paid by the users, and fee from other amenities such as parking and rental spaces. Provision of support facilities such as drinking water, toilets and showers, solid waste management, 24/7 security, power backup.',1,'With the DBFOM (User pay) model the concessionaire assumes the revenue risk, provided with freedom, flexibility and motivation to develop, operate and generate rate of return to recover the project lifecycle costs. Such arrangement entails the responsibility of revenue collection as well as demand generation is vested with the Private Partner. During operations, the private partner will share revenue with the Implementing Authority in form of a variable payment (Annual Concession Fee), which will be the bid parameter With this model, the Implementing Authority shall create an enabling environment for successful development of the project that shall be attractive for investors.',1,'Survey launched during the Feasibility Study enabled the council to understand the current situation from the target beneficiaries viewpoint. Interview was conducted with 106 drivers and car owners, 96%, stated that if a parking facility will be established within the vicinity, they will be supportive of it. Some of the project benefits identified included: (1) more order in the streets, (2) better security for vehicles, (3) possibly lesser accidents when parking, and (4) people can use side streets for walking, biking. These perceived benefits influence the high acceptability of the project from the viewpoint of the target beneficiaries, indicating that the proposed project will bring about positive impact on the overall well-being of the public.',1,'The various facilities proposed within the car parking complex include Parking bays for cars and two-wheelers, Equipment used for collecting parking fee and parking management system , Closed circuit television system, information kiosks / enquiry counters, fire detection, suppression and evacuation systems as well as other amenities.',1,'',1,3.46000,8297.00000,0,0,0,NULL,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,1,NULL),(39,39,13,'ocds-aaaaaa-39',1,'Located in a village, 12 Kms North of the capital in Unguja, Chuini is a critical junction which attracts lots of public utility vehicle (PUV) traffic (from Bububu/town, North A and West A) but lacks a bus terminal and formal market with adequate facilities to manage high volume of buses/ daladalas and accommodate buying and selling of goods in the locality. WAMC intends to develop a bus terminal facility with adequate capacity to handle the increasing traffic of public transport. Without bus terminal facility, the PUV at Chuini are operating along the main road reducing the effective road carriageway. During the rush/peak hours, situation becomes worse with more vehicles on the road, which is unsafe for commuters. This has prompted the West A Municipal Council to propose for a bus/ daladala terminal with a commercial complex.',1,'Provision of departures for daladalas/buses, pedestrian entry/exit points of the bus terminal building, pedestrian circulation/movement, seating spaces for passengers in waiting areas, departure, alighting and idle/staging bays, parking bays for private cars and two wheelers, collection of terminal fee revenue, schedule/information display system, closed circuit television system, rest rooms / toilets, information kiosks, complaint desks, public address system, drinking water faucets/taps, waste management as well as pest control and fire safety',1,'Implementing this project under PPP modality will provide avenue for the private sector player to design, develop and operate the project on a long term basis, giving full freedom and flexibility to create a robust revenue stream for the project, take the requisite measures to develop the project into a hub within vicinity. Under the PPP model, the project will also develop skills, expertise and business acumen of the PSP. The proposed Project may be proceeded with the typical Design, Finance, Build, Operate, Maintenance and Transfer (DFBOM) with core project responsibility lying with Concessionaire and the IA mainly managing & monitoring the concessions as per the terms and conditions contained in the PPP Agreement. The role of the IA will be restricted to the management of the Concession throughout the Concession Period and see to it that the mandatory development obligations carved out for the Concessionaire in the PPP Agreement shall be performed by the Concessionaire during the term of the PPP Agreement. However, the Project being a complex in nature, the IA need to assist the Concessionaire in marketing the facilities to the general public to attract/ and further increase the influx of users, by endorsing the same. The monitoring will be through an Independent Expert who shall perform its functions based on the terms laid out in the PPP Agreement.',1,'Survey was launched during the Feasibility Study enabled the council to understand the current situation from the target beneficiaries viewpoint. Interview was conducted with 42 drivers interviewed, 42 passengers, and 84 traders. Thus, in the survey conducted, 85% of the respondents stated that if a terminal facility with commercial spaces for rent will be established within the vicinity, they will be supportive of it. Some of the project benefits identified included: (1) comfort and safety, (2) better security in the area, (3) better/cleaner environment may impact on health and eliminate hazards, and (4) potential to attract tourists to use public transport or purchase items from the commercial complex. These perceived benefits influence the high acceptability of the project from the viewpoint of the target beneficiaries, indicating that the proposed project will bring about positive impact on the overall well-being of the public.',1,'The various facilities proposed within the bus/daladala terminal include 58 boarding bays , 29 alighting bays, 174 idle/staging bays, vehicle and pedestrian circulation areas, passenger concourse, terminal schedule (information display) with public address system, scheduling system, driver retiring room, information kiosk/ enquiry counter and complaint desks, security system, service centre for minor repairs of buses and other vehicles, firefighting system and power backup, commercial spaces, market facility and other support facilities.',1,'',1,7.60000,18238.00000,0,0,0,NULL,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,1,NULL),(40,40,14,'ocds-aaaaaa-40',1,'Jumbi is along the way to the South Region of Unguja in which about 154 hotels and resorts in Zanzibar are located. The South or Kusini Region is the topmost choice in tourism, followed by the North or Kaskazini Region, however, West B District does not have an existing market. Households rely on the already congested markets in the Urban District which are Mwanakwerekwe and Mombasa Markets which also serves the West A District and the South Region. There are also upcoming township developments in Tunguu. Currently, road construction works are underway from Fuoni to Tunguu, and further developments are anticipated. Because of this, there is increasing demand for basic infrastructure. The lack of a central trading area in West B, a basic infrastructure that could boost the local economy, has resulted to a variety of issues. This prompted the West A District Council proposed for the establishment of a modern market with commercial building in a strategic location in Jumbi. The proposed market will be fully equipped with all market amenities (like parking, universally accessible design, pathways, public conveniences, etc.) with improved energy efficient design along with adequate commercial space and some office space.',1,'Making available the commercial spaces for utilization and collection of fees in form of fixed monthly rentals from users of market facility and other amenities such as parking and rental spaces. Provision of support facilities such as drinking water, toilets and showers, solid waste management, 24/7 security, power backup.',1,'With the DBFOM (User pay) model the concessionaire assumes the revenue risk, provided with freedom, flexibility and motivation to develop, operate and generate rate of return to recover the project lifecycle costs. With this model, the Implementing Authority shall create an enabling environment for successful development of the project that shall be attractive for investors.',1,'A survey was launched on 83 traders for the project. Of this 71% are presently trading around the proposed project location, while 29% are holding business in the central business district in Mlandege. From the first group or respondents, viewpoints on their present condition of trading were obtained, as well as their perceptions on the proposed market stalls component of the project; while from the second group, their views on the commercial space component were elicited. The survey was important to understand the current situation from the target beneficiaries viewpoint In the survey conducted, 88% of the traders presently conducting business in Jumbi and nearby Mombasa Dragon Market stated that if the project will be established within the vicinity, they will be supportive of it. Meanwhile, among those who are currently operating in the central business district, some 79% expressed interest to venture into another business in the proposed project in Jumbi. Some of the project benefits identified included: (1) comfort and safety, (2) better security in the area, (3) better/cleaner environment may impact on health and eliminate hazards, and (4) potential to attract tourists to purchase items from the market and commercial complex. These perceived benefits influence the high acceptability of the project from the viewpoint of the target beneficiaries, indicating that the proposed project will bring about positive impact on the overall well-being of the public.',1,'The various facilities proposed within the market complex include commercial stalls, shops and ATM, Office Space for market administration office and rental, parking for cars and two wheelers as well as other amenities such as community hall, prayer room, open space and pedestrian walkways.',1,'',1,4.85000,11633.00000,0,0,0,NULL,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,1,NULL),(41,41,5,'ocds-aaaaaa-41',1,'Chakechake is among the two districts of the Pemba island, located in the South. The location of the Pemba airport makes Chakechake the gateway for tourism and one of the convergence points in the island. Many people from the different districts, commute daily via buses and daladala for various purposes such as work, and trading. In the midst of Chakechake town is the Machomanne market that caters for the day-to-day needs of households, and the general public. It is one of the public markets in Chakechake District and is 2.5 kilometres from the Chakechake Town. Machomanne market is housed in a decrepit old building where about half the stalls are unoccupied by a few traders, mostly in the morning but the market becomes almost empty by midday. There are some hardware shops, convenience stores and eateries, but some of the vendors are selling their goods on the floor. The current market does not have proper facilities to run smoothly, like parking, ventilated building, universally accessible design, pathways/ internal circulation, public conveniences, etc. The redeveloped market will be fully equipped with all market amenities with improved energy efficient design along with additional commercial space',1,'Making available the commercial spaces for utilization and collection of fees in form of fixed monthly rentals from users of market facility and other amenities such as parking and rental spaces. Provision of support facilities such as drinking water, toilets and showers, solid waste management, 24/7 security, power backup.',1,'With the DBFOM (User pay) model the concessionaire assumes the revenue risk, provided with freedom, flexibility and motivation to develop, operate and generate rate of return to recover the project lifecycle costs. Such arrangement entails the responsibility of revenue collection as well as demand generation is vested with the Private Partner. During operations, the private partner will share revenue with the Implementing Authority in form of a variable payment (Annual Concession Fee), which will be the bid parameter With this model, the Implementing Authority shall create an enabling environment for successful development of the project that shall be attractive for investors.',1,'During the surveys conducted at Feasibility Study stage, 37 traders were interviewed. This roughly represents about 40% of the estimated 87 traders that are currently operating in the market. Despite the dismal goings-on, a very positive disposition among the vendors and traders can be observed. According to them, the potential to attract more patrons to the market is high, if only the infrastructure can be improved. Thus, in the survey conducted, an impressive 91.7% expressed support to councils proposal for a much better market that will address the issues. Some of the project benefits identified included: (1) more potential clients/visitors in the market including tourists, (2) feeling of pride in trading, (3) better security in the area, (4) better/cleaner environment may impact on health, (5) more flexible trading hours. These perceived benefits influence the high acceptability of the project from the viewpoint of the target beneficiaries, indicating that the proposed project will bring about positive impact on the overall well-being of the public.',1,'The various facilities proposed within the market complex include commercial stalls, shops and ATM, Office Space for market administration office and rental, parking for cars and two wheelers as well as other amenities such as community hall, prayer room, open space and pedestrian walkways.',1,'',1,1.49000,3576.00000,0,0,0,NULL,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,1,NULL),(42,42,7,'ocds-aaaaaa-42',1,'Located at what could otherwise be a prime location, Mkokotoni market is a very busy market, where auctions for catch-of-the-day fish and other seafoods are carried out regularly. The market sits adjacent to the administrative offices of the North A District Council, along the road leading to most of the hotels and resorts in North A. It is presently used by traders as an importing and exporting venue of products via sea transport with Pemba Island. However, the rundown market is a heaven for flies and mosquitoes, and far from the sanitary and hygienic place where, especially, food items are sold for households in the area to consume. The stalls are also not uniform in space, and many vendors occupy the roadside, adding to the chaos brought by the lack of a proper parking area for vehicles and sidewalk for people. North A District Council proposed for the redevelopment of the Mkokotoni public market. The redeveloped market will be fully equipped with all market amenities with improved energy efficient design along with additional commercial space.',1,'Making available the commercial spaces for utilization and collection of fees in form of fixed monthly rentals from users of market facility and other amenities such as parking and rental spaces. Provision of support facilities such as drinking water, toilets and showers, solid waste management, 24/7 security, power backup.',1,'With the DBFOM (User pay) model the concessionaire assumes the revenue risk, provided with freedom, flexibility and motivation to develop, operate and generate rate of return to recover the project lifecycle costs. Such arrangement entails the responsibility of revenue collection as well as demand generation is vested with the Private Partner. During operations, the private partner will share revenue with the Implementing Authority in form of a variable payment (Annual Concession Fee), which will be the bid parameter With this model, the Implementing Authority shall create an enabling environment for successful development of the project that shall be attractive for investors.',1,'The North A District Council has held community engagements to gather traders opinions and support for the plan. The observations from the community engagements, and the results from the survey conducted at Feasibility Study stage, were consistent with regards to peoples anticipation of the proposed project. Some of the project benefits identified by the target beneficiaries included: (1) better/cleaner environment may impact on health and eliminate hazards (2) comfort and safety for all traders and buyers, (3) better security in the area, (4) potential to attract tourists to purchase items from the market, (5) having a feeling of pride and dignity in trading, and (6) more flexible trading hours. These perceived benefits influence the high acceptability of the project from the viewpoint of the target beneficiaries, indicating that the proposed project will bring about positive impact on the overall well-being of the public.',1,'The various facilities proposed within the market include two market blocks, meat shops, meat and fish stalls (sheds), auction platform, Bank ATMs, warehouse and cold storage, changing rooms and other amenities such as  parking for cars and two wheelers, truck loading and offloading, prayer room and garbage collection point.',1,'',1,2.65000,6349.00000,0,0,0,NULL,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,1,NULL),(43,43,6,'ocds-aaaaaa-43',1,'The Tunguu campus is designated as the main campus and the Universitys administrative base hosting about 38%, of the total student population. The campus is located about 15 kilometres from the urban centre. Currently, the key challenges being faced by the students is the lack of an in-campus accommodation. The Administration of the Tunguu campus is determined to address this issue in its commitment to ensure an enabling learning environment, including ancillary facilities, identified as important by the students themselves. The project will provide a safe heaven for students who will be living in-campus. For now, the private hostels that are off-campus are usually accessible through unpaved, unlighted dirt roads, which are surrounded by tall bushes. No security services are also provided. Such conditions are conducive for gender-based crimes or offenses and poses a lot of danger, especially to female students.',1,'Provide well illuminated rooms, maintain clean toilets, dining and common areas, maintain drinking water faucets in working conditions at all times, provide water supply and power backup, fire detection and suppression systems, public address system, internet and WIFI, security of project facility inside and outside of the perimeter, pest control and waste management.',1,'The recommended model to be opted for the Project is the DBFOM (Availability based Payments). One of the main reasons to opt for this model is that major revenue stream for the project is from the students and, in this case, IA is best placed and equipped to undertake this task. Implementing Authority can efficiently collect the hostel fee from the students along with the tuition fee. Also, it is best placed to exercise on the captive customers of this Project i.e. the students in case of non-payment of the hostel fee. This mechanism will allow building the confidence amongst investor and lending community in the Project.',1,'A survey on students in Tunguu was conducted for the feasibility study in relation to the highlighted need for an in-campus hostel. The survey was primarily designed to profile the students, understand current issues pertaining to accommodation, and elicit their willingness to shift and willingness to pay (WTP) should a hostel be built within the campus premises with 122 students, or 8% of the total student population in SUZA Tunguu campus for AY 2018/2019, enrolled in various courses. Those who currently live in private hostels or apartments near the campus comprised 47%, and 11.5% live with relatives or friends with houses nearby. In total, 58.2% are currently not living in their permanent residences with the primary reason of being near the campus. Of these students that have sought accommodation, 91.5% are paying rent and utilities. Average rent is Tsh135,000 per semester of four (4) months, with minimum at Tsh100,000 and maximum reaching Tsh320,000. Utilities being paid for include water, electricity and garbage collection service. These other fees total to an average of Tsh64,635 per semester. When asked about the reasons why they chose to live in a rental room, hostel or apartment, the reasons were: (1) practicality, as there will be savings on travel time and cost, (2) opportunity to focus more on studies, (3) monthly rent is not too high, and (4) the need for independence.',1,'The proposed for the Student Hostel Project are the two hostel blocks, two,  two Mess/ Canteen ,other facilities for each respective hostel (separately for boys and girls) central common, recreational room, mini common/study rooms, washing and drying area, hostel parking, commercial spaces including convenient / tuck Shops and a Shopping Center',1,'',1,2.96000,7110.00000,0,0,0,NULL,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,1,NULL),(44,44,1,'ocds-aaaaaa-44',1,'The water sector of Zanzibar is heavily reliant on groundwater extraction through a total of 303 serviceable boreholes. Each of these boreholes are operated by electric pumps. This results to a dependence on conventional electricity that is imported from mainland Tanzania, and thus, a direct competition for energy with the domestic and no-domestic energy requirements of Zanzibar. The heavy dependence of the water sector to the imported electricity supply in the islands is a major area for worry. The expenses on electricity to power the water extraction are fully subsidized by the national government, including payroll and other operating expenses. The water sector is now seriously looking into tapping renewable resources, such as solar power, in which the tropical islands of Unguja and Pemba. With the start of an new source of electricity supply for running the water pumping stations from solar power, it will ensure the uninterrupted water supply to the people of Zanzibar.',1,'Operating and maintaining the project assets including providing earthing and lightening protections, emergency response system and security of the project facilities',1,'The recommended model to be opted for the Project is the DBFOM (Availability based Payments). The reason behind the same is that under this model, there will be no entitlement with the Private Player to collect any user fee/ charges and the payment during the operation and maintenance of the Project Assets shall be done by the Implementing Authority to the Private Player from a dedicated fund created by the Implementing Authority for making Service Payments to the Private Player. The Concessionaire and its lenders shall have confidence in the Project as they shall receive fixed Service Payments.',1,'',1,'Solar PV modules, Mounting system, Invertor, Batteries, Allied equipment/fittings like cabling, junction boxes, earthling, lightning arrestor, switch, bidirectional meter, ACDB and DCDB, Security and safety system',1,'',1,3.47000,8331.00000,0,0,0,NULL,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,1,NULL),(45,45,7,'ocds-aaaaaa-45',1,'24% of resorts, hotels and guesthouses in Zanzibar are found in North A, making it one of the top destination of tourists. Because tourism industry is thriving in this part of Unguja Island, and local population is constantly growing, waste generation has also been increasing. Daily, the North A District reports a collection of 50 tons of garbage done by its designated service provider, Zanrec. Other service providers also collect waste from clients with whom they have direct contracts. Of the total waste collected, 60% to 70% are estimated to come from the resorts and hotels. Tourist generates about 1.5 kg to 2.0 kg per day which is higher than the estimated 0.55kg/capita/day of residents and a total of about 120 tons per day is generated in North A, and only 50 tons is collected and transported to the dumpsite at Kijini. There is no solid waste management program that includes an environmentally-sound waste disposal facility to accommodate the increasing garbage generation in the area. Currently NADC and the private company hired by Council, only cover part of commercial establishments and urban wards. Most of the rural wards are uncovered. Private service collectors dump the collected garbage in inconspicuous places, which are either designated by the district council or not. As relayed by the PMT, the present collection and transportation system is limited only to some resorts, hotels and one village. For those whose wastes are not collected, people resort to dumping in open spaces or on the street or digging pits and burning within the yard. Lack of proper SWM are well have huge impacts on health, environmental quality, and the society; when waste-related problems have already blown out of proportion, the effect becomes economy wide. With the local economy is highly dependent on tourism, ecological quality of the environment, through SWM, is of paramount importance. Under the proposed PPP project, the coverage of SWM will improve and the contracts will ensure that all parts of Council and all types of waste generators like hotels, markets, institutions, industries, households, etc. will be covered with robust SWM mechanism. With proper mechanism in place with PPP project, people will not burn wastes ad more waste will be collected and disposed.',1,'The scope of the Project in terms of service offering includes collection, transport, segregation, and disposal of Municipal Solid Waste generated by the identified Waste Generators in the area falling under the jurisdiction of the North A District Council along with Management of Mlilile Landfill Site. Operation and maintenance of the landfill operation with leachate management, landfill gas management, storm water management as well as monitoring surface and ground water quality. Managing public relations unit or a grievance redressal cell to interface with and attend to suggestions from users, government agencies, media and other agencies by the private partner.',1,'With the DBFOM (User pay) model the concessionaire assumes the revenue risk, provided with freedom, flexibility and motivation to develop, operate and generate rate of return to recover the project lifecycle costs. With this model, the Implementing Authority shall create an enabling environment for successful development of the project that shall be attractive for investors.',1,'The North A District Council has held community engagements to gather opinions and support for the plan. A survey was launched at the Feasibility Study stage on local residents and hotels who were invited for a brief forum. There were representatives from 10 hotels and resorts, with minimum capacity of 10 to a maximum of 250 guests, and 28 household heads. According to the respondents, the issues they face with the current situation include inefficiency in collection and transportation such as the irregularity in the service provision. The observations from the community engagements, and the results from the survey were consistent with regards to peoples anticipation of the proposed project. Some of the project benefits identified by the target beneficiaries included: (1) better/cleaner environment may impact on health and eliminate hazards (2) eradication of diseases caused by undisposed waste, (3) potential to attract more tourists in the area to support local economy, and (4) employment opportunity. These perceived benefits influence the high acceptability of the project from the viewpoint of the target beneficiaries, indicating that the proposed project will bring about positive impact on the overall well-being of the public.',1,'Landfill construction comprising of landfill cells, leachate pond, contaminated storm water pond, screening/ segregation area, equipment and garage, office, weighbridge, Toilet block, water storage, ground water monitoring well and buffer zone. Solid Waste collection, transport equipment as well as Personal Protective gears.',1,'',1,4.72000,11337.00000,0,0,0,NULL,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,1,NULL),(47,47,3,'ocds-aaaaaa-47',2,'Zanzibar imports its bulk petroleum products (kerosene, aviation fuel, petrol and diesel) through the Mtoni terminal on Unguja Island. The terminal is located in a World Heritage buffer zone and adjoins tourism and residential areas. The Mtoni terminal no longer meets the needs of Zanzibar: It is too small to meet growing demand. Because of encroaching urban development, expansion is not possible; Shallow draughts, aggravated by silting, constrain the size of vessels that can berth. Increasingly frequent shipments are required from small vessels, adding to transport costs and fuel prices in Zanzibar; Inefficient operations also add to transport costs and fuel prices; The potential for oil spills is too high; and Small storage capacity means that security of supply is not assured. This project therefore contemplates construction and operation of a high standard petroleum terminal, on Unguja Island, in the Bumbwini/Mangapwani region of approximately 380 hectares, 22 kilometres north of the existing Mtoni terminal. This will allow larger shipments and more efficient handling, thereby minimizing shipment costs. The unloading times of shippers and loading time of buyers will be reduced. Increase storage capacity and better access by vessels will improve security of supply. The project will be implemented in an environmentally sustainable manner. The risk to human life and the environment will also be reduced by re-locating the facility away from environmentally and culturally sensitive urban areas.',1,'The private partner shall install sufficient storage capacity and the necessary systems to ensure that stock outs do not occur at the importation facility to reduce the cost of fuel in Zanzibar and improve energy security. The private operator will also collect revenues on a commercial basis from customers using the facility. The terminal fees of the private operator will be approved by ZURA to ensure that the monopoly position of the operator is does not lead to higher prices for consumers.',1,'The proposed form of contracts are Build operate transfer (BOT) or Design, Build, Finance, Operate and Maintain (DBFOM) whereby, private partner will be responsible for financing, installation, operation and maintenance of the ZLT facility for the period specified in the agreement. The public partner will provide the exclusive right to the private partner to import petroleum products for the local market. All fuel products will be covered with the exclusion of LPG. Competition will be allowed in the LPG sector as there is already an operator in Mangapwani with advanced plans to develop a liquefied petroleum gas (LPG) importation facility under a ZIPA permit.',1,'The primary stakeholders are the oil marketing companies (OMCs), ZURA, Zanzibar Port Corporation (ZPC), Ministry of Infrastructure, Zanzibar Maritime Authority (ZMA) and consumers. There appears to be good support for the project from the primary stakeholders. There are, however, some potentially competing private sector operations in planning that may express concerns in been displaced by ZLT.',1,'Jetty, inclusive of dolphins, loading platform and trestle, piles and foundations, and piping; the tank farm; utility and building works; and transport infrastructure.',1,'',1,40.00000,96000.00000,0,0,0,NULL,1,NULL,'2020-06-25 06:36:24',NULL,NULL,NULL,1,2);
